td.paragraph: Lyme immunoblot testing should only be performed on
samples from patients who have had a Positive or
Equivocal result in a screening assay.
As per CDC criteria, a Lyme disease IgG Immunoblot must
show reactivity to at least 5 of 10 specific borrelial
proteins to be considered positive; similarly, a
positive Lyme disease IgM immunoblot requires
reactivity to 2 of 3 specific borrelial proteins.
Although considered negative, IgG reactivity to fewer
specific borrelial proteins or IgM reactivity to only
1 protein may indicate recent B. burgdorferi infection
and warrant testing of a later sample. A positive IgM
but negative IgG result obtained more than a month
after onset of symptoms likely represents a false-
positive IgM result rather than acute Lyme disease.
In rare instances, Lyme disease immunoblot reactivity
may represent antibodies induced by exposure to other
spirochetes.

considerations.

of diabetes.
Currently, no consensus exists regarding use of
hemoglobin A1c for diagnosis of diabetes for children.

td.paragraph: On
today's visit, we arranged for routine lab work as well as apolipoprotein B,
lipoprotein A, vitamin B12, and magnesium. An EKG was completed on today's
visit for further evaluation of her cardiac health that showed NSR and LBBB. An
echocardiogram was completed for further evaluation of her shortness of breath
upon exertion as well as her chest pain and heaviness. Preliminary images
reviewed and discussed that revealed a preserved ejection fraction. For her
complaints of dizziness and lightheadedness, we will arrange for a carotid doppler
today. Preliminary images reviewed and discussed that revealed mild-to-moderate
atherosclerotic plaque. For her significant lower extremity discomfort, we arranged
for an ABI/PVR today that revealed an RLE of 1.1 and an LLE of 1.21. Upon
physical examination, her right radial access site is noted to be healing well
without any hematoma, drainage, signs of infection, or abnormal bruising or
discoloration. We arranged for a right upper extremity arterial doppler on
today's visit for further evaluation of her right radial access site. Preliminary
images reviewed and discussed that revealed patent flow. For her significant lower
extremity swelling, heaviness, and aching, we arranged for a venous reflux
study today. Preliminary images reviewed and discussed that revealed no
evidence of DVT and a significant reflux bilaterally. An MCT monitor was placed
today to further evaluate and capture her episodes of palpitations and chest
pain. We will be providing her with a script on today's visit to obtain a cardiac
MRI to further evaluate her chest pain. We will also be sending her a script
for hydrocortisone cream for relief of her groin rash. All questions and
concerns were answered and addressed and a heart-healthy diet and healthy
lifestyle was encouraged and endorsed. She is to follow-up on Wednesday or
sooner should symptoms worsen and progress or should new symptoms arise. She agrees
to the plan of care.

Time Spent: Total time spent 75 minutes in face-to-face conversation, examination, reviewing records, discussing treatment options and procedures, pathophysiology, and anatomy. Diet and lifestyle modifications were discussed in great detail. Images were personally reviewed by me in front of the patient and/or family member and explained on our graphic diagram. Treatment options, risks, benefits and alternative treatments discussed with the patient in detail. All questions and concerns answered.
